{
    "attributes": {
        "action": "Allow qualified professionals to end a tenancy for adults who lack capacity",
        "additional_details": "Under current law, if an adult who lacks capacity needs to move into residential or nursing care and has no attorney or deputy, their tenancy can only be ended through the Court of Protection. This can take many months, leaving vulnerable adults paying rent for a property they no longer occupy and at risk of significant arrears. Allowing qualified professionals to act in a person\u2019s best interests would prevent avoidable debt and ensure timely, safeguarding focused decisions.",
        "background": "Adults who lack capacity can't end a tenancy, & Court of Protection delays mean they may owe rent on homes they no longer live in. The law might not protect them from avoidable debt. Allow healthcare or social workers to end a tenancy when in a person\u2019s best interests & no attorney or deputy exists.",
